1. Tag Mutability (Mutable)
Definition: By default, ECR repositories are Mutable.

Behavior: You can push an image with an existing tag (e.g., my-app:latest) multiple times. Each time you push, the tag is updated to point to the newest image version.

Pros: Easy to manage, especially if you constantly want latest to always point to the most recent code.

Cons: Risky. It makes your deployments non-deterministic. If your production environment is running my-app:latest, you cannot be 100% sure which specific build is currently running, as the tag could have been overwritten by a developer five minutes ago.

2. Tag Immutability (Immutable)
Definition: When set to Immutable, a tag cannot be overwritten once it is pushed.

Behavior: If you try to push an image with a tag that already exists in the repository, ECR will reject the push with an error (ImageTagAlreadyExistsException).

Pros: Highly recommended for production. It ensures consistency and traceability. You know exactly which code is running because a tag always points to a specific, unique image digest. If you need to update, you must use a new, unique tag (e.g., v1.1, v1.2).

Cons: Requires better CI/CD versioning discipline (you cannot just "re-tag" an image).




